{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_tango_ver02/data/sn84026749/100492593/1908050301/0685.xml":{"full_text":"The Iceberg Has Gentled the Volcano and\nTamed It to Eat From His Hand\u2014Regarded\nas One of Greatest Achievements in Ameri\ncan Diplomacy\u2014John Barrett Points Out\nOpportunities It Has Opened Up.\nHIS is the story of hov~ the\nGreat American Jceberx\ncooled and so~thed the\nlatin American Voleano,\ngentied and tamed it to eat\nfrom his hand.\nIt Is the stery of 2 diplomatic\nparadox.\nBlihu Root, Secretary of State, is\npopularly regarded as the coldest man\nin Americar. public life. lie has been\ndescribed as a \u201cfrozen intellect.\u201d The\nblood in his veins, they say, is con\ned. He is not supposed to have\nsympathy with or understanding of\nthe passions and weaknesses of other\nmen. He may have an emotion Now\nand then but he keeps It carefully\nhidden beiin4 the inscrutable mask\nwhich serves him for a face. It would\nbe difficult to imagihe Elihu Root\nswayed by !mpulse or sentiment.\nNo one doubts that tite blood of\nLatin-America Is steaming. boiling.\nsizxling hot. Surcharged with sentu\nment, impulsive in all things, the\nLatin-Americans erupt &t the drop of\nthe het. Always there are huge gobs\nof molten lava in their immediate\nvicinity. Passion runs riot south of\nthe Rio Grande.\nYet Root and the l.atin-Americans\ngot together, looked into each other's\nfaces, and undarstood. The distrust\nof years vanished, and confidence was\nbegat. \"Twas as if a magician had\nwaved his wand and little white doves\nsuddenly filled the cage where queru\nlous magples had been. The \u201cYankee\nFaril\"\u201d the bogie man of LatinAmert\ncan dreams, ran screeching for the\ntall timbers. We went to bed one\nnight feared, but little respected. Next\nmorning we were the \u201cbig brother\u201d\u2019\nof the smaller republics to the south\nof us.\nthroughout all Latin America, from\nMexico and\nHow did Root do it? He was aimost\nthe lasr man you wouid have picked\nto send cn a distrust-allaying mission\nto thoge hotspurs who live around the\nequator and beyond. You wouid have\nsaid that of all eminent Americans he\nwae the least likeiy to understand the\nLatin- Americans or to be understood\nby them. You, would have heen wrong.\nof course, hut your judgment would\nhave had almost aniversal support.\n\now w\nIf we are going to acquire an under\nstanding of the Root prestidigitation\nwe have got to go back a bit. Euro\npean powers had cultivaied TLatin\nAmerica more assiducusiy\u2014and m\ninteiligently\u2014than we has done. Every\nnow and then a prince of the blood\nroyal went there on a friendly visit\nEurope's men of letters, her artists,\nand her statesmen deemed well speat\nthe time required for a journey to the\nSouthern American republics. All of\nthe Latin-American capitals are cen\nters of culture, lilerature. and art.\nWe either did not know this, ejzse we\nignored it. Between the capitals of\nEurope and the cap'tals of Latin\n5\nw\nx ap\nWhen Uncle Joe Canon was first\nelected Speaker in 1902, he had for\neompetitors Sereno E. Payne and\nJames S. Sherman of New York and\nJohn Dalzell of Pittsburg. Mr. Cannon\nwas elecied on the first ballot. Asked\nto explain his easy victory, Uncle Joe\nsaid: \u201cWhile Payne. Dalzell. and\nSherman were hustling around for\nTUTTE een I TT ey Tee\n-_\u2014 a. er\n\u201cY& Is Right, Ole II:3. T2235 Yo' Mouf Shet or Dey Will Put a Hoe in Yo\nLan\u2019 and Kk ov Gv to Wail\n\n10W ELIHU ROOT\u2019S FIRST WORD CLINCHED THE\nFRIENDSHIP OF PAN-AMERICANS FOR UNCLE SAM\nRoet\u2019s Magic Wand.\nSTORIES ABOUT WELL-KNOWN PEOPLE IN THE NATION'S CAPITAL\nF\n\n\n\n\n\n\na\u2014 w\u2014\u2014n\nMay 3, 1908\nAmerica there was the bond of fe!\nlnwship In higher things.\nThought Only of Dollars.\nw w\n_ Our interest in Latin-America aid\nnot extend beyond the dollars te be\ngot out of her. This fact probably\nnever took concrete form in our own\nmines, but Latin-America saw and un\nderstood it. Our men of letters, our\nartists, and our statesmen did not\njourney to Latin-America; they went\nto Europe in droves, byt it did not\nseem to occur that there were things\n2 the south worthy of acquaintance.\nur \u201cdrummers\u201d went there and capi\ntalists seeking opportunity of exploita\ntion, and these, aside from Lhe mems\nbers of our diplomatic and consular\ncorps, were the only Americans they\never saw.\nThe bulk of Latin-Americans, there\nfore, conceived us a nation of money\ngetters, without men of larger at\ntainments. The better informed knew\nwe had great statesmen great artists,\nand great writers jand they resented\nthe fact that our statesmen, artists,\nand writers ignored the existence of\ntheir own men of like accomp.ish\nments.\nThen, one day, two years ago, the\nannouncement went forth that Elihu\nRoot, the premier of the American\nCabinet, was going to South America.\nMr. Root had not at that time been\nlong at the head of the State Depart\nment, but long enough for Latip\nAmerica to know him as one of ou\u00bb\nforemost statesmen and probably our\ngreatest living lawyer. Members of\nthe Latin-American diplomatic corps\nin Washington were enthusaistic, and\nthe enthusizsm manifested Itself in\nthe dispatches they sent home. They\ndescribed Mr. Root as the greatest\nliving American, and as this could be\nonly a matter of opinion, they had a\nright to their own. The enthusiasm\nswept in a great wave over ail Latin\nAmerica. The newspapers published\ncolumns and columns about the Ameri\ncan Secretary of State, until his career\nwas probably much better known in\nLatin-America than at home. The\ngovernments and the people prepared\nto give him the greatesi welcome ever\naccorded a foreigner.\nSuspicion {rent In.\nThen came the reaction which the\nmercurial Latin cannot escape. Sus\npicion crept in. Some one asked: Why\nis Secretary Root coming to South\nAmerica? What does he want? Is\nnot some hidden, sinister motive be\nhind his visit?\nThe ecld wave followed the hot wave\nand overtook it. Preparations for lis\nentertainment went forward, but en\nthusiasm was suspended. LatinAmer\nica wanted to know how Root was go\ning to treat her before she laid her\nhomage at his feet. Perhaps he would\nbe menacing-\u2014she was prepared to be\ndefiant. Perhaps he would be patron\nvotes, I remained right at my home in\nDanville and did nothing but saw\nwood. Many reporters came to inter\nview me, but I had nothing to say.\nWhen I was a boy, I told one reporter,\nwho was more insistent than the oth\ners, a circus was advertised to ap\npear in our neighborhood. I wanted\nto go to that circus the worst way,\nPorm a\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nin wealth in wisdom, and in spirit, probably is no man so well quaiifi\nbut our conception of the true way to to speak as John Barrett, director\nMom\nasncsoarmaliahd *hia fo mat +a mr? Acer he Rurraayy of Amer! an Remus\nizing\u2014she was prepared to be resent\nful. Perhaps he would lack in under\nstanding-\u2014-she woul: give him just that\nmeasure of politeness demanded for\nthe stranger within her gates.\nWashington was not unmindful of\nsthis change in latin-American tem\nper toward the approaching visit\nClearly Mr. Root\u2019s misbion was most\ndifficult. A misstep, a fsise note, a\n\"word. wrongly spoken would plast all\nhope of the things he hoped to achieve.\nMr. Root's first speech was to be de\nlivered at the third conference of\nAmerican Republics at Rio de Janeiro,\nJuly 31. Sixty millions Latin\nAmericans, from the Rio Grande to\nMagellan's straits, awaited that\nspeech\u2014with judgment still suspended.\nEvery newspaper in La\u2018in-America\narranged to have it telegraphed.\nIt overs owed every other thing in\ninterest.\nFirst Sentence ti:e Kev.\nFARA DOIOIIvE Ma BS.\nIn almost his first sentence this\ncold, unemotional, incisive man from\nthe North found the key to Latia\nAmerican hearts.\n\u201cI bring from my country,\u201d he sald,\n\u201ca special greeting to her elder sisters\nin the civilization of America.\u201d\nHer \u201celder sisters\u201d In the ofiviliza\nand my father had a negro hand\nnamed Eph, who was also anxious to\ng0.t0 the coming show. Between us\nwe managed to scrape together enough\nmoney to pay our way into the circus.\nph toted me on his back most of the\ndistance to the town, where the show\nwds advertised to appear. On enter\nwag the tent we proceeded past several\ncages in the menagerie department,\nuntil we came to a big cage contain\ning an enormous ape.\n\u201cHow is yo\u2019? said Eph, stopping\nand :iving a profound bow.\n\u2018No answer.\n\u2018How is yo'?\u201d repeated Eph a lit\ntle louder, with another bow. Still\nthere was no response, \u2018Wherzapon\nEph drew pack and, shaking his head,\nsaid sagely: \u2018Yo is, right ole man.\nKeep yo mouf shet or dey will put a\nhee in yo' han\u2019 and mek yo go to\nwor La\nw w\n\nRepresentative Foster of Vermont,\nwho, it is believed, is slated to be\nelected to flil out Fedfield Proctors\nurexpired term in the Senate when\nthe Green Mountain Stats Legisiature\nmeets next winter, will be a great\nacyuisition to the Senatnrial story\nteller's club at the north end of ile\nCapitol.\nA ST\nRecently Mr. Foster joined a group\nof statesmen v-ho were discussing the\npolitios] and business outlook.\n\u201cYes,\u201d he obscrved when if came\nhis turn to pass a remark, \u201cthe inlus\ntrial situation is pretty bad, but it is\nimproving and in a short time things\nwill be normal again In the business\nworld. Changes occur ery rapidly .in\nthis country,\u201d he add<d. \"Did I ever\ntel! you about the man who strueh\nSan Francisco stone bro'e during a\nfinanc'al depression. No? Well, this\nman landed in the Pacific coas* metro\n\n_pells without a cent and began imme\ndiately to hvnt werk. He finally ob\ntained the offer of a job as bdbrake\nman on a froishr \u201crain that was abont\nto stort Eas:. Tie was told that the\nroy won'd he 3 cents a m'le and as\nthat sermcd to he the only thing In\nsi=ht he took it. When the train\nreached the foothills and began climb\nnz the mountains its progress became\nvery slow. It just crept along and\nthat wes all. \"Great Scot?\u201d exclaimed\nthe man, \u2018at the rate we are going 1\nwill not be able to earn enough to buy\na drink in twenty-four hours\u201d Some\ntime afterward when the trair had\nalmost reacha1 the tor of the divide.\nrt hroe in two ard the par! my brake\nman was on fegan flying back down\nthe mountain at a tremendous rate of\nCopyright. 137, by Underwood Underwood.\nSECRETARY ELIHU ROOT.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES MAGAZINE\ntion of America. It was the match\n\u00abnat started the conflagration. The\nenthusiasm that broke loose was all\nthe more demonstrative beacause of its\nsushension during the period of sus\npicion. He could have made nu strong\ner appeal to Latin-American pride,\nand when you have appealed to a Lat\nin-American\u2019s pride half the conguest\nof him is over,\nTheres isn't a school boy in Latin\nAmerica \u2018who can\u2019t repeat that sen\ntence, and much more of Mr. Root's\nspeech.\nIf the Latin-Americans wished for\nany assurance of Mr. Root's and his\nGovernment's Intentions was not\nlacking. \u201cWe wish for no victories. but\nthose of peace.\u201d he said; \u201cfor no ter\nritory except our own: for no sover\neignty except the wm 'versignty over our\nselves. We deem t .e independence and\nequal rights of the s\"azilest and weak\nest member of the family of nations\nentitled to as much respect as those\nof the greatest empire, and we deem\nthe observance of that respect the\nchief guaranty of the weak against\nthe oppressipn of the .st We\nneither claim nor desire any ts, or\nprivileges, or powers that we do not\nfreely concede to every American re\npublic. We wish to increase our pros\nperity, to expand our trade, to grow\n\u2018Don\u2019t jump,\u2019 yelled the conductor,\nwho was an old railroad man, to the\nney brakeman, \u2018hold on tight!\n\u2018Jump,\u2019 sald tne brakeman with\nfine scorn, \u2018well 1 guess not. What\nkind of a2 fool would I be to jump\nwhen I am making at least $2.50 an\nhour?\nw\nSenator Burnham of New Hanpshire\nltkes a joke even when it is at his\nown expense. The face gf the junior\nSenator from the Granite State is\n\u2018Don\u2019t jump!\u2019 Yelled the Conductor.\u201d\nclean-shaven. and his head is almost\nequally devoid of hatr. Several rears\nage he made a trip eut to Oklshoma\nas a member of a Senatorial svbeHm\nmittee, The editor of the local paper\nwhere the subcomimiitee made its first\nstop. to show his enterprise and ap\nnreciation of the honor of the Sena\ntorial visitors\u2019 presence, came ou with\na special edition with cuts of the\nparty. The editor was shy om cuts; ail\nIn wealth in wisdom, and in spirit,\nbut our conception of the true way te\naccomplish this is not te pull down\nothers and profit by their ruin, but to\nhelp friends to a common prosperity\nand a common growth, that we may\nal become greater and stronger to\nw J\ngeration.\u201d ne said, \u201cto predict that the\nnext twenty years will witness a de\nThey Believed Root.\nHere was the crux of Latin-Ameri;\ncan politics. Tt is true the same as\nsurances had been given before, but\nthey had not come first hand, and\nwere not convincing. Here was the\nAmerican Secretary of State, grave,\ndignified. with sincerity in his voice.\nlooking inte thelr eyes and telling\nthem they had nothing to fear from\nthe big republic to the north. And\nthey believed him.\nThat speech marked tre beginn'ng\nand the finishing of Root's conquest of\nLatin-America. He made ot aer\nspeeched, all able, all tactful but it\nwas that first speech that reached\nthe sixty millions of Latin-Americans\nand stuck in their minds. In some of\ntne republics, it is seriously said, the\nspeech i= to be printed in the school\nbooks. and its substance made a part\nof the education of every LatinAmeri\ncan boy and girl.\nWith the elaborate fetes the bhan\nquets, the receptions in \"onor of Sec\nretary Root this story doves not neces\nsarily have to do. The thing of in\nterest now is results, the results ap\nparent a year and a half after the re\nturn of Mr. Root from his Latin\nAmerican visit. On this subject there\na eH a\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 E\u2014 a\nhe had ir stock was a collestion that\nhad been forwarded with some atent\nmedicine advertisements of the before\nand-after taking class. The cut as\nsigned to Mr. Burnham had long\nwhite whiskers, and a thick head of\nvery long hair of the Buffale Bill pat\ntern.\nTo add a further bit of realism the\nOklahoma editor told in His \u201cwrite\nup\u201d just how each member of the\nparty looked and acted.\n\u201cJust here,\u201d the account proceeded,\n\u201cour distinguished fellow-townsman,\nColonel Wiggins, clapped old man\nBurnham on the back and asked Rim\nI\u2019 they had anything in old New\nHampshire bigger than Woodward\ncounty, Okla.\n\u201cOld man Burnham studied min.\nute, ran his fingers through his oiled\nwhiskers, bit ofi the end of a cigar\n(Senator Burnham does net smoke),\nand sald with a way down East\ndrawl: \"Well, there are the White\nmountains; they are chock full of\ngranite, and will furnish more tomb\nstones than will probably be ever\nneedad In Oklahoma.\u201d\nSenator Burnham has carefully pre\nserved a copy of the newspaper giv\ning this vivacious account of his visit\nto that far Western country. He says\nthat it will come in handy in helping\nhim to prove an alibi if he should ever\nhave the misfortune to be accused of\nnigh crime or misdemeanor.\nw\nLeslie M. Shaw, of Iowa, formerly\nSecretary of the Treasury, has a storv\non tip to At almost every situation thrt\npresents itself. He was governor\nlowa when President Roosevelt !.o\nvited him to become a member of his\nvabinet. He went to Washington an\nresponse to a summors from the White\n\u2018House. While Mr. Shaw's appoint\nment had deer rumored. it had oot\nbeen announced ofheially, and a per\nsisieprt rumor was in circulation to the\neffact that ne would not accept e\u00ab\nCabinet offer. Several! correspond ns\nwaited on Mr. Shaw at his hotel. iv\njearr his intentions regarding the mat\nter.\n\u201cXhen I \u2018was a boy,\u201d he sad, \u201c1\nstarted off one day on a fishing Up\nwith another bod. We had a lonz\ntramp tc the fishing place and as the\nweather was warm we got very thirsty\nand coming to a farm house my com\npanion suzzested that we stop and ga!\n2 Aarink of water The lady of \u2018the\nhouse not only gave us a drink out of\na nice tin dipper, but insisted upon our\ntaking some rie. Bill. my com-anion,\ntock a large plece, but from diffidence\n_\nbably is no man so well qualified\no speak as John Barrett, director of\n\u201che Bureau of Amerizan Republics. So\nsought Mr. Barret\u00ae\n\u201cIt is no idle prophecy or an exag\n5%\nCugba south to Argentina\nand Chile, which will excite the ad\nmiration of the entire sorid. To the\nman whe has not studied our sister\nrepublics this m=y seem a very broad\nstatement. To him, on the ocher hand,\nwho has trawgled thro) ji these coun\ntries and has investigate] their re\nsources and possibliVies, it will ap\npear as entirely logical.\nvelopment or forward movement\n\u201cEvery citizen of the United States\nshould take the keenest irfsrest in the\npast history and in the pi-sent condi\ntion of these nations to the south of\nus, because our count;y has more at\nstake politically and commercially in\nthat part of the world than has any\nother nation or group of nations. It is\nour greatest field of commercial oppor\ntunity. It is 3 section of the world\n\u2018where our moral influence and exam\n\u201cle can count for more than anywhere\nelse. All Iatin-America is today\nwatching us closely to see and deter\nmine whether we are entitled to lead\nership among the American nations\nwhether wer are worthy of their confi\ndence, whether we are pointing out\nthe road they should follow hetter than\nthat which Europe would show them,\nand, finally, whether we are sincerely\ninterested in them as sister nations\nor something, I declined. Bill looked\nat me with ams woment, \u2018Les\u2019 he said,\n\u2018always help .yourself to pie when it\nis passing.\u201d That was pretty sound ad\nvice, \u201cand I have scted on that prin\nciple ever since!\u201d\nw w\nTro last time Willlam J. Bryan was\nat the National! Capital he told a story\nat his own expense, concerning his\nearly career as an orator. The inci\ndent he related 00k place several\nyears before Mr. Bryan sprang Into\nnational promineace as a Presidential\ncandidate.\n\u201c1 stumped my State,\u201d he said. \u201cIn\na lively ubermatosial contest, and\nmade red-hot speeches agains: the Re\nHabltcas candidate. I said such se\nth that I thought at the\nis that might prove to be a little\nembarrassing If I should ever meet the\nly. The\ncan e was elected, and a \u2018short\ntime afterward I accepted an invita\na meeting\nin\nthink that !t was an entertainment\nfor the blbenefit of some charity IT\nver an I\n\u201cThe Lady Insisted Upon Our Taking Some Pie.\u2019\nfzanily. or RIES\n\u201cA great obligation, moreover, rests\nand as members of the pan-American\nupon toe\nAm\n\npeopie, upon the American press and\nupon American business men, travel\ners, and sciolars to tke advaniage\nof the work for, friends! ip and mutoal\n\u201cIt may require the passing of maay\nyears and the cunciusions of future\nhistorians to fuilybring out all the re\nSuils thar came from Mur. BooUs dipio\nmatic mission to our sister nativus,\nbut there is ao question \u2018iar he ac\ncompiished more by (nal one visit\ntkan could have ween done in scores of\nyears of ordinary diplomatic proced\nure. He wo} ite cunndence and eo\nteem of the raln-Anericans from the\nLune he mace is Hrst grout speech wi\nthe pan-amencan conierence in Rig\nJaneiro; and, with Lis other succeed\ndig deciarariols of opinion in Uragi ay,\nin Argentina, in Chile, in Ferd, ins en\nama, and iu Colombia, unili he return\ned back tv the Uniteu Siutes i Octo\nver, he increased the respect of the\nLaun-Americaus for his mincerity and\nHdevewped a true leeiing of good will on\ntheir part woward the united States.\neonfidencre which Elihu Roo accom\nplished in his journey =z nd Soull\nAmerica, and, later on Ougn Mes\niow.\n\u201cIn conileung, i would say tnat (Le\nInternational isureau of the American\nKepuplcs, uf wiicn have the ooner\nto ve the direcior, Las ample evidences\nvery day of wr praciical resuits of\nMr. Koot's {ihe couseguent\nnew glowln of laicrest (nn Latiz-Amers\nica, in the grea! correspondence that if\nis carrying on with people in ai pars\nof the western Leinisphere who desire\nto familiarize (bhemseives with van~\nAmerican development and progress.\u201d\n4 yor\nBa gy, SRE a i Ts\nStudents of our history and dipic~\nmacy piace Eilhu Root's \u201cconquest\u201d\nLatin-America as one of our great\nest diplomatic achievements\u2014one eof\ncan people. They rank it with Frank\nHn's giplomatic victories In Europe\nduring revolutionary times, with Jef\nferson\u2019's purchase of the Louisiana\nterritory, with Seward's purchase of\nAlaska, and, more modernly, with\nJohn Hay's triumphs in Oriental dipio\nmacy.\nthe fruits of peaceful endeavor which\nwill be of lasting benefit\nNor did Root's policy end when he\nreturned from Latin-America. He is\nstill pursuing it with visible results.\nA few vears ago members of the\nLatin-American diplomatic corps aid\nnot have much standing at Washing\nton. Our Government and the \u201c\u2018so\ncial set\u201d at the National Capital ap\npeared to regard them somewhat in\nthe Nght of necessary evil. They\nwere accord\u00e9d courtecus treatment,\nbut not scught. Since taking hold of\nthe State Department Mr. Root has\npaid special artention to South Amert\nean diplomats, and their standing has\nbeen very much improved. not only in\nGovernment official circles and the\nDiplomatic Corps. but in society gen\nerally. This is very gratifying of\ncourse, to the Latin-Americans and ft\nalso makes the road of owr inter\ncourse with them much smoother and\nefficacicus.\nRoot\u2019's visit paved the way for the\nwonderful reception accorded Admiral\nEvans\u2019 fleet on its journey around\nSouth America, and the voyage of the\nfleet increased the new respect Latin\nAmericans have for us.\nIt is now \u201cup to\u201d che American\nbusiness man. If he doesn't profit by\nthe lesson Root has tauzcht him, and\nreap the iHon's share of lLatinAmeri\n\u2018can trade it will not be bocause Latin\nAmerica is not in a receptive mood.\nSS =F \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014tm\u2014 Simm a \u2014m\u2014\u2014 SS\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014\nknow that there were several speakers\ndown on the program; aiso a number\nof singers, Ae aOvVernur-eiect pre\nsided. The chairman of v2 entertain\nment committee introduced the speak\ner or singer to the governor, and he\nwould (nen preseal them io the amn~\nalence.\n\u201cWhen it came my iurn to be pre\nsented (0 the governor. I had some\nmi=zivings as to the reception he\nwould give me, on account of the bit\nter speeches had made in the came\npaign. The governor gave me a pieas\nant smile, however, and. iurning te\nthe audience he said:\n\u201cLadies and gentiemen, I have the\nhonor of presenting te you William J.\nBryan'\u2014then. turning to me, and in\nstage whisper that could be heard, it\nseemed to me, half way across the\nhouse said: \u2018Singer or speaker. Mr.\nBryan?\n\u201cThat experience kept my head ain\nswelling. The governor and 1 after\nward became good friends, but he told\nme that he had actualiy never heard\nof me before the Omaha meeting I\nhave mentioned. And I had been un\nder the impression that my\nin that campaign had stirred the\nState from end to end\u2122\nGreat Diviomatic Trinmoh\nPage Three","height":"34784","width":"26608"}}
